description.narrative:
The Haute Kotto knows regularly attacks by armed groups against the populations. This chronic crisis in Central African Republic isat the origin of many displacements, kidnappings and deaths. OXFAM has already worked in the emergency response (WaSH, EFSL and Protection) in Bria following the attacks by armed groups against the populations  also occurred in November 2016, financed by CHAF andHF. After a relative improvement, where IDP's returned to their original neighbourhoods, the humanitarian situation deteriorated again as a result of clashes between these armed groups (Anti balaka # AB and FPRC - Patriotic Force for the Renaissance of the Central African Republic) form 8 May 2017, in the city of Alindao and Bangassou and after in Bria (17 May 2017). The consequence is the displacement of nearly 40,000 people on the 6 sites in Bria (Catholic Mission, Bornou 1 and 2 Hospital, Eblise centre and PK3). The affected people are obliged to live in IDP sites in very challenging conditions (no access to safewater, no shelters, very bad hygieneconditions and very dangerous situation in term of security). PK3, for instance, was a site arranged for 2.088 and at this moment 38.439 IDP are present. Multi sector assessments are ongoing.
In the current context, very basic humanitarian response has been putting in place to address the vital needs of displaced populations (OXFAM, COOPI, IMC and MSF). The different medical actors (IMC and MSF) present do not have enough contingency to respond to the magnitude of theemergency and it is imperative to be able to cover basic needs in terms of access to water hygiene and sanitation. The populations affected by this crisis moved to sites in fear of fighting between the various armed groups. These massive displacements arecarried out in precipitation. Populations are highly exposed to water-borne diseases today, as they fetch water from superficial sources. Emergency sanitary infrastructures on site are insufficient and open defecation is mainly practiced (creating sanitary and protection risks). Up to date Oxfam has been providing 40m3 of chlorinated water per day with water trucking, which is totally insufficient.  The markets are totally inactive (the majority of the population are on the sites). At the local level, the authorities were already fragile or even absent at different levels due to the chronicity of the crisis and the remoteness of the capital Bangui and its administration. Government response capacity is totally non-existent. OXFAM is the only expert organization in the field of WaSH and Protection on the proposed areas of intervention and is working in straight collaboration with COOPI #Cooperazione Internazionale (Camp Manager). OXFAM has a logistic, human capacity and an expertise in this field enablingit to be rapidly operational.
The activities financed by CATFUND will enable to:
1. Supply of drinking water through water trucking (80m3/day);
2. Establishment of excreta collection facilities in the 6 sites (100), segregated by sexand age (children);
3. Installation of shower on different 6 sites (100);
4. Hygiene promotion.
